'''Charles Peter Allen''' [[Member of Parliament|MP]] (2 December 1861 <U+2013> 18 September 1930)<ref>[http://www.scrum.com/wales/rugby/player/647.html Charles Allen rugby profile] Scrum.com</ref> was an [[England|English]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician who represented [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]] from 1900-1914. His professional career was as a [[solicitor]] and newspaper journalist. He served his country during World War I, as a major in the [[Gloucestershire Regiment]], and as a sportsman played international [[rugby union|rugby]] for [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]].

==Personal history==
Charles Peter Allen was born in 1861 in [[Prestwich]], Lancashire to Peter Allen, the manager of the [[Manchester Guardian]] and part owner of the [[Manchester Evening News]]. In 1865 the family moved to [[Beaumaris]] on the Isle of Angelsey in [[Wales]], when they rented a property. The family purchased a house in the town in 1873.<ref name="Bangor RFC"/> Allen was educated at [[Rugby School]], before matriculating to Oxford University. On leaving university he was articled to a firm of Manchester solicitors, and qualified as a barrister, though by 1887 he had changed careers and became a journalist for the Manchester Guardian. He was assigned as a foreign correspondenet and was sent to Russia, Bulgaria and Turkey.<ref name="Bangor RFC">[http://www.bangor-rugby.co.uk/allen.htm Charles Peter Allen biography] bangor-rugby.co.uk</ref> While in [[Constantinople]] he met Evaline Barker and the two were married in the city in 1899, before returning to live in Beaumaris. They had five children, four daughters and a son.

In 1900 he became Member of Parliament for Stroud, and he and his family moved to the area. While a MP, Allen was made a [[Privy Council]]lor.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jenkins |first=John M. |coauthors=et al. |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Rugby Players |year=1991 |publisher=Bridge Books |location=Wrexham|page=13 |isbn=1872424104}}</ref> He retained his position as MP until 1914, when he resigned his post to join the British war effort during World War I. Allen had been a member of the Territorial Volunteers of the 2nd and 5th Battalion of the Gloucestershire Regiment prior to the outbreak of war, and at the age of 53 he was made a full time soldier. Posted to France, he became a Town Mayor, dealing with troop movements.<ref name="Bangor RFC"/> At the end of his military career, Allen had reached the rank of major. In 1922 he ran again for the Parliamentary seat of Stroud, but was beaten. He died at his London home in 1930.

==Rugby career==
Allen first came to note as a rugby player when he was selected for [[Oxford University RFC]], though he had also represented Rugby School as a youth. Allen played in three [[The Varsity Match|Varsity Matches]] against [[Cambridge University R.U.F.C.|Cambridge University]], winning three sporting 'Blues' from 1881 to 1883. In 1884, Allen was selected to play for Wales in the opening match of the [[1884 Home Nations Championship|Home Nations Championship]] against his birth country, England. Under the captaincy of [[Charlie Newman]], Wales lost by a goal to a goal and two tries, though it was Allen who scored the only Welsh [[try]], the first points the Welsh team had ever scored against the English.<ref>[http://www.wrexhamafc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10311~1217234,00.html WRU recognises North Wales] wrexhamafc.co.uk, 17 January 2008</ref> Allen was reselected for the next game of the tournament, in a home game to Scotland. Wales lost the game, and Allen was replaced for the final game by [[Cardiff RFC|Cardiff's]] [[William Norton (rugby player)|William Norton]].

